Biden</strong>=E2=80=99s declining health, that spell has been broken. Inde=
ed, the same people who turned a blind eye to the president=E2=80=99s menta=
l state are now buzzing about <strong>Jake Tapper</strong> and <strong>Alex=
 Thompson</strong>=E2=80=99s forthcoming book, <em>Original Sin</em>, which=
 promises an =E2=80=9Cunflinching and explosive=E2=80=9D accounting of Bide=
n=E2=80=99s reelection campaign =E2=80=9Cdespite evidence of his serious de=
cline=E2=80=94amid desperate efforts to hide the extent of that deteriorati=
on.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:0;"><br/>There=E2=80=99s
been a reckoning among past members of Biden=E2=80=99s inner circle, too. I=
 recently sat down with <strong>Michael LaRosa</strong>, the former Biden o=
fficial and longtime <strong>Jill Biden</strong> spokesperson, during a pan=
el at American University=E2=80=99s Sine Institute, where I=E2=80=99m a fel=
low, to discuss the 2024 election and his unvarnished perspective on the Bi=
den =E2=80=9Ccover-up,=E2=80=9D such as it was. LaRosa, who left the White =
House in 2022, pushed back on that specific characterization, but acknowled=
ged efforts to
hide Biden from the media with remarkable candor=E2=80=94describing the pre=
sident=E2=80=99s press team as essentially =E2=80=9Cgaslighting=E2=80=9D th=
e American public. The following conversation has been edited for length an=
d clarity.</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
