9999999997px;"><span style=3D"word-break:break-word;"><strong>Media Optics =
&amp; =E2=80=9CGaslighting=E2=80=9D</strong></span></h3>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<table width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" role=
=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspace:0pt;word-b=
reak:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td style=3D"padding-bottom:32px;"><div style=
=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;=
;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:150%;text-al=
ign:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;"><strong><em>Tara Palmeri</em>: You worked so closely with the Biden fam=
ily for years. I have to ask, do you
think it=E2=80=99s accurate, as </strong><strong><em>Original Sin </em></st=
rong><strong>states, that there were =E2=80=9Cdesperate efforts to hide the=
 extent of [Biden=E2=80=99s] deterioration=E2=80=9D in 2024?</strong></p><p=
 style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margi=
n-bottom:0px;"><em>Michael LaRosa</em>: There are many things there that ar=
e true, in my view. Calling it a cover-up is a little harsh and exaggerated=
=2E Every politician, every human being=
, tries to cover up their age. We all=20=
wear makeup on TV.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><br/>So we w=
ere always, from day one, cognizant that age was an issue. From the moment =
I joined the campaign in the fall of 2019, it was a problem. I was recently=
 quoted in the lead of a <em>Wall Street Journal</em> piece by <strong>Anni=
e</strong> <strong>Linskey</strong>=E2=80=94I love her, she=E2=80=99s a goo=
d reporter, though I felt a bit like my quote may have been misconstrued. T=
he story began with me saying that I was asked to walk back my comment to a=
 reporter for
<em>The Des Moines Register</em>, who asked me to confirm the number of cou=
nties Jill Biden had visited. I had worked for her as her traveling press s=
ecretary, and the reporter was working on a profile of Jill. When I mention=
ed that conversation to her chief of staff [<strong>Anthony Bernal</strong>=
], he wasn=E2=80=99t happy, because they were hyperaware that if she=E2=80=
=99d been going to more counties than Biden had, that would provoke more di=
scussion about his age.<br/><br/></p><p style=3D"margin:0;
margin-bottom:0px;"><strong>She looked like she had more stamina and like s=
he was on a campaign.=C2=A0</strong></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:=
0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Yes. And look, the=
 spouse is the supporting actor. I was not thinking about the boys team. I =
was thinking about my job, which was to promote my boss. But I was still, a=
t the time, learning that this is a supporting role. I=E2=80=99d worked for=
 two senators, the speaker=E2=80=99s office, and a congresswoman. I
was used to promoting everything the principal is doing. In this case, the =
principal was the spouse, who, by the way, will probably go down as one of =
the most influential first ladies we=E2=80=99ve ever had, because of the ag=
e thing.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"=
margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong>Well, that=E2=80=99s the story right n=
ow=E2=80=94that it was Jill running the ship. And that was the story with R=
onald Reagan and F.D.R. There have
</strong><strong><em>always</em></strong><strong> been stories that, with a=
n aging president, the wife has to swoop in and do the job. Like when Dr. J=
ill Biden attended a cabinet meeting.</strong></p><p style=3D"margin:0;marg=
in-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">She was =
there because she was speaking on behalf of her initiative, the health init=
iative.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong>But you get the
optics.=C2=A0</strong></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</=
p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">We were an integrated part of th=
e West Wing, because we didn=E2=80=99t have our own agenda. We went and cha=
mpioned [Joe Biden=E2=80=99s] agenda all around the country. Unlike <strong=
>Hillary</strong> and other first ladies, the only issue Jill wanted to wor=
k on was giving credit to her husband. It=E2=80=99s a long way of answering=
 your question, but =E2=80=9Ccover-up=E2=80=9D is probably a little too har=
sh.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margi=
n:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong>Here=E2=80=99s another quote from the book:=
 =E2=80=9CBiden, his family, and his team let their self-interest and fear =
of another Trump term justify trying to put an, at times, addled old man in=
 the Oval Office for four more years.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</strong></p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><br/>There are some things that are true, =
like the gaslighting. There was a lot of denial of the polling. All of the =
polling in the
spring of 2023, and then the fall of 2023, showed that there was no real de=
pth of support from his own party, let alone independents and Republicans. =
And Biden had been tied, or within the margin of error, with Trump=E2=80=94=
who had, by that point, how many court hearings? How many indictments? The =
fact that he was so close was always a problem, but they were kind of in de=
nial.<br/><br/></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">The message to =
everybody was to make sure you tell people, =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s too early=
=2E
These polls don=E2=80=99t mean anything.=E2=80=9D Then for about a year and=
 a half, the numbers never moved, and by denying the data that was out ther=
e publicly, by denying and undermining the really insightful journalism tha=
t <em>The</em> <em>New York Times </em>was doing, that you were doing, and =
all of the free press, they were actually demeaning a lot of those people.<=
/p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;=
margin-bottom:0px;">It was the data denial that really bothered me,
because we loved polling when we were running right. We=E2=80=99re going to=
 go on <em>Howard Stern</em>, [but] we=E2=80=99re not going to talk to <em>=
The New York Times</em>? They were doing that in spite. But what they didn=
=E2=80=99t understand, and what they <em>still</em> don=E2=80=99t get, is t=
hat it can=E2=80=99t be either-or. You can=E2=80=99t choose to alienate cer=
tain constituencies, and certain audiences, just for the sake of pandering =
to another.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;"><br/>Anyway, the point is that they <=
em>did</em> do a
lot of gaslighting. If you were watching MSNBC, you probably believed them.=
 But if you were consuming information, consuming <em>data</em>, and lookin=
g at it objectively, and trying to interpret it and process it objectively,=
 none of it was surprising.</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
